    en: "Tenants in New York have a statutory right to form, join, and participate in a tenants' association. The landlord cannot retaliate against a tenant for organizing. The main statute is Real Property Law 230, backed up by the retaliation ban in RPL 223-b. A tenants' association gives residents collective power to address shared problems: repairs, safety, rent increases, and communication with the landlord. The right applies in buildings of any size — from a duplex to a large complex — and in public, subsidized, and private housing. Many tenants do not know this right exists."
